      <div class="intro-text">

                      <h1 class="_title post-title">Statement Addressing Student Concerns</h1>
              
              <div class="post-meta">
    <div class="post-date-line">
            <span class="post-author">President and Vice President</span>
      <span class="pipe-separator">|</span>
            <span class="post-date">Posted on <strong>October 11, 2019</strong></span>
    </div>
          
    <section class="social-sharing-links" role="region" aria-label="Share this Article on Social Media">
            <a class="popup" href="https://facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fusg.uic.edu%2Fnews-stories%2Fstatement-addressing-student-concerns%2F&p[title]=Statement Addressing Student Concerns - ">
        <svg aria-label="Share this on Facebook" width="36" height="36" viewBox="0 0 36 36" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
          <title id="share-link-facebook">Share this on Facebook</title>
          <g fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd">
            <ellipse class="_circle" fill="#001E62" cx="18" cy="18" rx="18" ry="18"/>
            <path class="_mark" d="M21.57 33.6V21.2h3.887s.364-2.385.54-4.874H21.59V13.08c0-.484.633-1.138 1.256-1.138h3.01c.033-.75.2-2.88.36-4.942h-4.504c-6.08 0-5.937 4.75-5.937 5.462v3.882H12V21.2h3.775v12.646c.727.102 1.47.154 2.225.154 1.227 0 2.42-.138 3.57-.4z" fill="#FFF"/>
          </g>
        </svg>
      </a>
                  <a class="popup" href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https%3A%2F%2Fusg.uic.edu%2Fnews-stories%2Fstatement-addressing-student-concerns%2F&text=Statement Addressing Student Concerns - ">
        <svg aria-label="Share this on Twitter" width="36" height="36" viewBox="0 0 36 36" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
          <title id="share-link-twitter">Share this on Twitter</title>
          <g fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd">
            <circle class="_circle" fill="#001E62" cx="18" cy="18" r="18"/>
            <path class="_mark" d="M26.525 12.688c.89-.53 1.573-1.372 1.894-2.374-.833.492-1.755.848-2.736 1.04C24.898 10.522 23.778 10 22.54 10c-2.38 0-4.31 1.92-4.31 4.292 0 .336.038.664.112.978-3.58-.18-6.756-1.89-8.88-4.485-.372.634-.583 1.37-.583 2.158 0 1.49.76 2.802 1.915 3.573-.706-.023-1.37-.216-1.952-.537v.053c0 2.08 1.485 3.814 3.456 4.207-.363.098-.743.15-1.136.15-.277 0-.547-.027-.81-.077.547 1.706 2.14 2.947 4.025 2.98-1.476 1.153-3.334 1.838-5.353 1.838-.347 0-.69-.02-1.027-.06C9.907 26.29 12.17 27 14.604 27c7.925 0 12.258-6.54 12.258-12.21 0-.187-.003-.373-.013-.557.842-.604 1.572-1.36 2.15-2.22-.772.34-1.603.57-2.475.675z" fill="#FFF"/>
          </g>
        </svg>
      </a>
                        
    </section>
    </div>
        
            <figure class="captioned-image">
    <img src="https://usg.uic.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/267/2019/10/Clear-USG-Logo-2full-copy-copy-1090x595.jpg" alt="USG logo ">
      </figure>
    
          <p class="_subtitle">Regarding the threat to campus this week</p>
    
              <div class="page" title="Page 1">
<div class="layoutArea">
<div class="column">
<p>The President and Vice President have released a statement responding to the concerns of students following an online threat to campus.</p>
<p>Addressing Student Concerns Regarding Threats:</p>
<p>On Wednesday, October 9, 2019, we were startled to find out about anonymous threats to the University of Illinois at Chicago campus that could have potentially intruded on the safety of occupants of campus. As did many students of the university, we did not take these threats lightly and looked to administration to express that same urgency and concern. The communication with students, faculty and campus at large from the UIC Police Department and other entities, did not reflect the weight felt by students and the UIC community. The email speaks to larger problems with communication and mental health on campus that the student body desperately wants addressed.</p>
<p>We expect that leadership, first and foremost, makes the safety of students on this campus a priority. We also expect that they provide clarity about their approach to ongoing matters of safety, in ways that uphold the integrity of investigations but also address student concerns. These threats raised concerns about the physical safety of students but also invaded their mental and emotional safe spaces. We as student government leaders expected a more empathic response in which an understanding of the political and social implications were addressed.</p>
<p>As we understand students have many questions regarding the investigation of these threats from the UIC Police Department and the response from administration; we are working on an opportunity for a public meeting. We will release the time and date as soon as possible. Until then, concerned students are invited to attend our upcoming General Assembly meeting on Monday, October 14 at 6 p.m. in SCE 302. We are developing a list of questions that we will be expecting them to answer. If you have questions or concerns please voice them here: https://forms.gle/Awtxvzy6fwCB3aBJ7 for consolidation purposes.</p>
<p>In closing, we wholly condemn movements rooted in patriarchal oppression that insight violence against any person, with deep awareness that these threats of danger are a symptom of larger issues. Every student on our campus has a right to a safe learning environment, which includes access to essential on-campus mental health services. We will continue to advocate for the increase of resources for both the counseling center and other crucial spaces that support student mental health. We urge professors to excuse the absences of students who felt unsafe to commute to campus due to the threats of violence.</p>
<p>Yours in Community,</p>
<p>Aliemah Bradley | Undergraduate Student Government President, usgpresident@uic.edu<br />
Taylor Holmes | Undergraduate Student Government Vice President, usgvicepresident@uic.edu</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

    
  </div>

